The percentage of people employed in the agricultural sector has reduced, whereas the nonagricultural sector has clambered. India is emerging as a strong economy. Nevertheless, it has a long way to go ahead.
* 100 years ago women gained the right to vote and stood equal with men in a country matrimonial parliament. In several legislative assemblies, women constituted a sizeable percentage of voters and they utilized the ancient right of voting to effect a noticeable impact in democratic politics. In the capital city of India, Delhi, the electors included 80,000 women. It was the biggest single electoral unit. The number of women who voted in numbers enlarged over time. In Tamil Nadu there was a 30 per cent increase between the 1937 elections and the 1939 general election.
* Gradually, women emerged as members of limited constitutional bodies.
* Loko Suva, a voluntary organization founded in 1909, played a prominent function in organizing women and in developing their awareness.
* The Ain’tugafix (Burma) Act in 1937 enabled women to take bare of their children after the death of their husbands without any male intervention.
Conclusion: India has come a very long way since the 1980s. But a long journey still lies ahead before the country attains the level in education, literacy and health that it has aimed at. India is gradually growing as a global economic power and gaining its influence in global politics. But
